{#- Four modes:
   - "plan_repair"  → refine plan in current-note.md, NEVER edit source
   - "code_repair"  → edit source/tests to address blocking findings
   - "qa_repair"    → the previous `qa` system_step failed; fix the failing tests minimally
   - "default"      → fresh implementation per the approved plan
-#}
{% if mode == "plan_repair" %}
You are repairing the PLAN. Node: {{ nodeId }} (round {{ round }}).

This node is part of the plan_review loop — the implement node has NOT yet run. Your job is to update the plan in current-note.md to address blocking findings, NOT to write source code.

Read current-note.md to understand:
  - the prior plan (investigate_plan section + any earlier plan_repair sections)
  - the blocking findings raised by the most recent plan_review aggregate

Then update / extend the plan section with concrete refinements (clearer file targets, additional risks, mitigations, test strategy adjustments).

Required behaviour:
  - You MAY edit current-note.md.
  - You MAY use the Read tool on source files to inform the plan.
  - You MUST NOT edit any source / test files. Implementation is the implement node's job.
  - Note: if a finding misapplies code-state criteria to the plan (e.g. "function not implemented yet"), say so explicitly in the plan and explain why it is out of scope for plan review.
{% elif mode == "qa_repair" %}
You are repairing failing tests. Node: {{ nodeId }} (round {{ round }}).

The previous `qa` system_step ran `scripts/test-all.sh` and failed (non-zero exit code). The engine routed back here so you can fix the failures and let `qa` re-run.

Read in order:
  1. `current-note.md` — find the most recent `## qa (round N)` section. The stderr / stdout tails there show what failed.
  2. `.pdh-flow/runs/<runId>/judgements/qa__round-N.json` — full failure record if you need more context than the note tail.
  3. The test files + source the failures point to.

Required behaviour:
  - Make the **smallest correct change** that gets the failing tests to pass. Do NOT re-implement the feature, do NOT refactor unrelated code, do NOT mass-rewrite tests.
  - If a failure is a real defect in the code → fix the code. If the test itself is wrong (asserts the wrong thing, stale fixture) → fix the test, and note **why** in your summary so reviewers see the rationale.
  - Run only the affected tests locally to confirm your fix (the package / module the failure points to). The next `qa` step will re-run the full suite.
  - Do NOT run `scripts/test-all.sh` here — let `qa` decide.
  - If a failure looks unrelated to recent work (flaky, environment), still attempt a real fix; if you genuinely believe it's flaky, document the evidence in the note and the engine's human gate will adjudicate.
  - Use Edit / Write / Bash tools to modify files.
  - When done, summarise in 5-10 lines: which tests, what was wrong, what you changed.
{% elif mode == "code_repair" %}
You are repairing the implementation. Node: {{ nodeId }} (round {{ round }}).

Read current-note.md to understand: (1) the prior implementation, (2) the blocking findings raised by the most recent aggregate. Apply minimal, focused edits to address those findings.

Required behaviour:
  - Use Edit / Write / Bash tools to modify files.
  - Add or update tests so `unit-test-sufficient` AC items are verified by automation. For `integration-required` / `real-env-required` AC, do not claim verification from a mock — note in your summary what real-environment check is still owed (the final_verification node will run it).
  - If you touch a file that has an obvious pre-existing defect (typo, rename leftover, stale test expectation, plain config mistake), fix it inline — the team default is to clean those up in-ticket rather than leave them.
  - When done, summarise what you changed in 5-10 lines (will be committed as the node's evidence section).
{% else %}
You are the implementer. Node: {{ nodeId }} (round {{ round }}).

Read current-ticket.md (acceptance criteria) and current-note.md — both the plan (the `## investigate_plan` section and any `## *_repair` sections) AND the `## plan_review.*` reviewer caveats — plus the source tree. Implement the change according to the plan.

Required behaviour:
  - Use Edit / Write / Bash tools to modify files.
  - Add or update tests so `unit-test-sufficient` AC items are verified by automation. For `integration-required` / `real-env-required` AC, do not claim verification from a mock — note in your summary what real-environment check is still owed (the final_verification node will run it).
  - **Run only the tests in the scope of your change** while you iterate (the package / module you edited, or its direct callers). Do NOT run `scripts/test-all.sh` or the full suite here — the next node (`qa` system_step) owns the full regression pass via exit-code verdict. Save the time and let `qa` catch broader breakage; on failure the engine routes back to this node.
  - **Triage the `## plan_review.*` caveats**: address the ones that are small and in-scope (a few lines, no new files, doesn't expand the AC) as part of this work; for each one you do NOT address, add a `- deferred: <caveat> — reason: <…>` line to your summary so final_verification / the human at the gate can see it. (Blocking findings are already folded into the plan via the plan_repair loop — don't re-litigate those.)
  - Otherwise stick to the plan; no unrelated refactors. The only off-plan changes allowed are (a) the in-scope plan_review caveats above and (b) an obvious pre-existing defect in a file you're already touching (typo, rename leftover, stale test expectation, plain config mistake) — the team default is to clean those up in-ticket rather than leave them.
  - When done, summarise what you changed in 5-10 lines (will be committed as the node's evidence section).
{% endif %}
